#	Data Source & Understanding

## Source of the Data

This project uses healthcare simulation data sourced from Emergency Room Simulation-Inspired Data available on OpenDataBay:

ðŸ‘‰ Emergency Room Simulation-Inspired Data
ðŸ”— https://www.opendatabay.com/data/healthcare/48a3cbc8-e1ab-4b9c-af06-dbf9b0ebadd6

The dataset is designed to model hospital emergency room visits with synthetic or de-identified records suitable for analytics and operational research. It does not contain personally identifiable information (PII) and may be used for analytical and educational purposes.

ðŸ“‚ Purpose of the Dataset

The dataset represents historical emergency room simulations and contains information useful for:

Analyzing patient flow patterns

Identifying utilization clusters

Supporting operational decision-making

Evaluating healthcare resource needs

In this project, the dataset is used to understand and segment patients based on visit behavior and usage patterns to support operational improvements.



##  ðŸ§  What the Data Represents

Each record in the dataset correlates with a simulated patient visit history, capturing attributes related to:

The number and frequency of visits

Time between visits

Visit duration

Patient characteristics relevant to clustering

This structure allows us to apply techniques such as K-Means and DBSCAN clustering to find distinct patient behavior segments.



## Key Parameters in the Dataset

Below is a table outlining the major fields in the data and their business relevance:

Field Name		Description			Business Relevance
Patient_ID		Anonymized patient identifier	Tracks unique patients for grouping
Arrival_Time		Timestamp of patient arrival	Used to calculate visit frequency
Departure_Time		Timestamp of leaving ER		Allows computation of visit durations
Visit_Duration		Time spent in ER (derived)	Indicates operational load per visit
Total_Visits		Count of visits (derived)	Key metric for segmentation
Days_Between_Visits	Average days between visits	Indicator of visit behavior patterns
Priority_Level		Severity code/triage category	May differentiate patient urgency
Other_Attributes	Additional simulation variables	Used for deeper pattern analysis

Note: Some attributes are derived during preprocessing (e.g., Visit_Duration, Total_Visits, Days_Between_Visits) based on original dataset fields.



## Data Characteristics
Type

Structured tabular data

Format

CSV or equivalent tabular format (loaded into a DataFrame)

Granularity

Each row represents a single patient or visit entity, depending on preprocessing

Use Case in This Project

This project uses clustering on visit metrics to find:

Frequently returning patients

Normal utilization groups

Anomalous or outlier patterns

Subgroups that may indicate operational concerns



##ðŸ§¹ Data Preparation Steps

To ensure high-quality analysis, the following preprocessing was performed:

Missing Value Handling: Removed or imputed blank fields

Derived Metrics: Calculated visit duration, total visits, days between visits

Feature Scaling: Standardized numerical values for clustering

Outlier Screening: Identified extreme values that could distort clusters

This preparation ensured the data was suitable for applying unsupervised learning techniques for segmentation.



## Why These Fields Matter

Each parameter contributes to understanding patient behavior differently:

Arrival and visit frequency: Identifies patients who use the ER frequently

Visit duration: Suggests complexity of care or system strain

Days between visits: Separates periodic vs sporadic utilization

Priority levels: Helps characterize patient urgency and potential resource needs

Together, these help identify:

High utilization cohorts

Routine or low-impact patients

Anomalous or unusual patterns

These insights can inform staffing, scheduling, and resource allocation â€” essential for healthcare operations.
